The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Bengal | Briefs
                                                                                                                     4                                                                                      BRIEFS
                  
	 Midnapore, July 13: The West Midnapore administration will distribute rice at Rs 2 per kg to tribals living in Maoist-affected areas.    
	Families with a monthly income of below Rs 2,000 will be eligible for the allotment. District officials said there were about 54,000 tribal families in Binpur block. Lalgarh falls in this area. The rice will be distributed through ration shops from August. We will distribute rice irrespective of whether the families have BPL (below poverty line) cards, said N.S. Nigam, the district magistrate. The authorities have also decided to distribute bicycles to tribal girl students studying in classes IX to XII.         
	 Calcutta: Police in West Midnapore were asked to escort a teacher to his school by the Calcutta high court. Benod Behari Bhuniya was allegedly not being allowed to enter the high school from where he had been suspended in 2004. The education department had in January called the suspension illegal.        
	 Burdwan: The CPM has called a 12-hour-bandh in Burdwan on Wednesday protesting an attack on three of their councillors by alleged Trinamul Congress supporters on Tuesday.
                                                                                                                                                      
